Name: Computer Supplies
MetaDescription: Everything for your computer from Choice Stationery Supplies. Offering next day delivery on PC supplies.
Description: Everything for your computer from Choice Stationery Supplies. Offering next day delivery on PC supplies.

Name: Stationery
MetaDescription: Stationery and office supplies from Choice Stationery Supplies with free next day delivery.
Description: Stationery and office supplies from Choice Stationery Supplies with free next day delivery.

Name: software
Description: Instructions for a computer's processor to perform specific operations e.g. system software such as Windows and iOS, application software such as internet browsers and apps.

Name: multimedia software
Description: Computer programs that allow information to be presented in various formats, such as text, audio and video.

Name: voice recognition software
Description: Computer programs that can understand the spoken words of the user. The software can do various things with the speech, such as convert it into text or use it to perform an internet search.

Name: desktop publishing software
Description: Computer programs where the layout, contents and typography of the document can be changed by the user so a professional-looking document can be present or published.

Name: computer utilities
Description: Computer programs that help your computer to perform better e.g. anti-virus software, disk repair software, file management software.

Name: print utilities
Description: Computer programs which allow users to manage printing devices.

Name: antivirus security software
Description: Computer programs which protect computer systems, files and software from computer viruses.

Name: networking software
Description: Computer programs which allow a user to set up, control and manage a network or networks between computers, printers and other devices.

Name: communications server software
Description: Computer program which controls a communications server, which is a carrier-grade computing system to control network infrastructure

Name: remote access software
Description: Computer program which allows you to access a data system from a remote location, for example through a VPN (virtual private network).

Name: components
Description: A hardware component of a computer such as a hard disk or memory.

Name: handhelds & accessories
Description: Portable computer devices and phones, and their accessories such as cables and stands

Name: telephone switching equipment
Description: Equipment that allows you to connect two or more different locations via telephone lines

Name: telephones
Description: Call your friends, business partners or customers with one of these great telephones!

Name: mobile phones
Description: A mobile phone, also known as a cellphone, mobile, or handphone, is an electronic telecommunications device with the same basic capability as a conventional fixed line telephone, but which is also entirely portable and is not required to be connected with a wire to the telephone network. With most modern cellphones you can do a lot more than just making phonecalls: with most models you can send an SMS or e-mail, surf the internet, play games, save phone numbers so you'll never have to write down or memorize them again and much, much more.

Name: mobile headsets
Description: A headset is just a combination of a headphone (with one or two ear plugs) and a microphone. Headsets with one ear plug are used mostly for calling hands-free, while the ones featuring a full headphone are better suited for communicating with your teammates in games.

Name: computers
Description: Device which is programmed to carry out a set of arithmetic or logical operations e.g. desktop computers, smartphones

Name: notebooks
Description: A notebook, also known as laptop, is a portable computer. When you are looking for the right notebook, it is important to know where you are going to work with it. Do you want to use it on the road? Choose a model with a special energy-saving 'mobile' processor, a good battery and a reasonably small display. This will allow you to work longer with the same battery and saves you the trouble of carrying around a large display that consumes a lot of precious battery power. Or will you be using you notebook mainly in places where you will have access to a power outlet? Then choose a desktop processor (more processing power for less money) and an ordinary battery. This will save you a lot of money, which you could then spend on a bigger screen.  You'll work faster because you can view more information at once and it's great for multimedia!

Name: notebook docks & port replicators
Description: A platform into which you can install a portable computer. The docking station typically contains slots for expansion cards, bays for storage devices, and I/O connectors for peripheral devices, such as printers and monitors. Once inserted in a docking station, the portable computer essentially becomes a desktop model computer. Most importantly, the same data is accessible in both modes because it resides on the portable computer's drives. The idea behind docking stations is to let you simultaneously enjoy the expansion possibilities of desktop model computers with the portability of notebook computers. In addition, the docking station enables you to use a full-size keyboard and monitor when you're not traveling.

Name: PCs/workstations
Description:
Personal Computers, PCs for short, are computers for personal usage. They always have the following components:

- A processor (CPU), this is the heart of your computer, where the data processing is done.

- Memory (RAM), this is very fast memory in which temporary data is stored before being processed by the processor.

- Motherboard, this is the component that connects all the different parts of your computer. Often it has some integrated components like a sound card, enabling your computer to play sound, or a network card, to connect your computer to the network.

- Video board, this is the part of your computer that is responsible for the graphics processing. Micro ATX motherboards often have an integrated video board. Those integrated video boards are generally not very well suited for playing games, but good enough for watching movies.

- Hard disk, this is the permanent memory of your computer where your data is stored.

- An optional DVD/CD player/recorder for reading/writing DVDs/CDs.

Name: RFID mobile computers
Description: Mobile computer which uses RFID (Radio Frequency Identification) e.g. scanning devices in shops and restaurants

Name: servers
Description: Extra powerful, extra reliable computers that have been specially designed for server applications. For example serving a website, a large database or shared storage space to a lot of users. Servers are often not very quiet and deliver hardly any graphical performance, which makes them not suitable for use as personal computer. If you need a lot of servers, choose a rack mountable model. Those models need less space and your server room will remain tidy.

Name: interface components
Description: A point of interaction between computer hardware or software and peripheral devices such as computer monitor or a keyboard

Name: graphics cards
Description: The graphics card, also known as the video card, is the complete graphical subsystem of the PC. It is responsible for the quality and speed of video processing. For users that wish to play games or work with multimedia applications, it is especially important to have a video board with a high performance graphics processor and enough memory.

Name: interface cards/adapters
Description: An explansion board you insert into your computer so the computer can be connected to a network

Name: networking cards
Description: A NIC or Network Interface Card is a circuit board or chip which allows the computer to communicate to other computers on a network. When connected to the network, computers can share websites, files, printers and other resources. The most popular networking standard at the moment is Ethernet, which one can recognize by the rectangular connectors with eight wires in them. Wireless network with the 802.11b and the faster 802.11g standard is also increasingly popular, both at home and in the office, though it is not yet as fast as wired (ethernet) network. A public place where you can use wireless internet is called a "hot spot".

Name: video capturing devices
Description: Devices that convert an analog video signal (such as that produced by a DVD or video player) into a digital signal which can then be shown on a computer.

Name: data input devices
Description: Devices that feed data into a computer e.g. keyboard, joystick

Name: graphic tablets
Description: On a graphic tablet you can write and make drawings with special pen. The information your graphic tablet receives is transferred to your computer and can be displayed as a drawing on your screen. With the appropriate software, it is even possible to write in handwriting on your graphic tablet instead of typing.

Name: keyboards
Description:
The keyboard is the main input peripheral used by all computers. The keyboard allows for user input and interaction with the computer. Much like many typewriters the keyboard has all the letters of the alphabet, numbers 0 - 9 and additional special operational keys, e.g. for adjusting the volume or going to your inbox directly. There are three different connection types:

- USB is the most modern. You can recognize it by the rectangular connector.

- PS/2 connectors are round. This type of connection is fairly commonly used by PC's.

- Bluetooth is another modern (wireless) connection method.

Name: mice
Description:
The mouse is the second most important way of communicating with a computer. Please be careful to choose the right type of connection when buying a mouse, there are three different types:

- USB is the most modern. You can recognize it by the rectangular connector.

- PS/2 connectors are round. This type of connection is fairly commonly used in PCs.

- Bluetooth is another modern (wireless) connection method.

Name: wireless presenters
Description: Device which is similar to a TV remote control and is used to wirelessly control a presentation on a computer such as on Powerpoint .

Name: scanners
Description: With a scanner you can make all your documents, pictures and photos digital.

Name: light pens
Description: Wireless computer input device which allows users to point to items on a screen on write and draw on screen.

Name: stylus pens
Description: Small pen-shaped instrument used to input commands onto a computer screen, mobile device or graphics tablet.

Name: mouse pads
Description: A mouse pad is very useful when you still have a mouse with a ball in it. It provides better grip for the ball on the surface, so you can work more conveniently with your mouse. For the newer optical and laser mice it is important to have an entirely flat surface to work on. Not all mouse pads provide this, so have a close look at the surface of the pad before buying it if you intend to use it with the latter kind.

Name: data storage
Description: Device able to store and retrieve data.

Name: disk arrays
Description: Group of two or more hard discs used to increase performance and enables fault tolerance.

Name: optical disc drives
Description: With these drives you can read and record DVDs and/or CDs in all kinds of formats. Please note the difference between DVD+R and DVD-R when buying a DVD burner, often drives can write only to one of those two media types, sometimes to both. When you buy a drive that only supports one type, you will always have to be careful to choose the right writable DVD discs in the shop. Newer DVD drives also support writing to Dual Layer DVDs. This kind of discs have a storage capacity of 8.5 GB instead of the usual 4.7 GB. DVD (re)writers generally can read and write CDs also, but only some CD (re)writers can read DVDs.

Name: tape drives
Description: Tape drives are a cost-effective solution for backing up all your important data when high speed is not required.

Name: tape arrays
Description: Racks that can hold a number of tape drives.

Name: tape auto loaders & libraries
Description: Storage device which contains one or more tape drive, a number of slots to hold tape cartridges, a barcode reader to identify tape cartridges and an automated method for loading tapes. A tape library with one drive is known as an auto loader.

Name: internal hard drives
Description:
Hard disk drives are today's fastest permanent storage media and have a large capacity. For this two reasons they are the most used storage medium in computers and servers. When buying a new hard disk, there are three important things to consider:

- The connection of the disk to the computer or other device you will be using it with has a big influence on the speed with which data can be read from/written to the disk. Make sure the connection of the disk you buy is compatible with your computer!

- The rotational speed is also important for the speed with which data can be read from/written to the disk and determines the time it takes to find a file on the disk.

- Last but not least, the storage capacity of the disk, i.e. the amount of data that can be stored on the disk.

Name: PC monitors
Description: TFT/LCD displays are perfectly flat, a lot thinner and lighter than conventional CRT displays and do not flicker, all this because of the new technology they use for producing images. Do you want to free up space on your desk, or do you want to be able to move your monitor without breaking your back? Then this is the perfect display for you!

Name: touch screen monitors
Description: Monitors, common on smartphones and tablets, which respond to touch.

Name: print & scan
Description: Ability to print and scan documents using a device such as an all-in-one printer and scanner.

Name: dot matrix printers
Description: A dot matrix printer or impact matrix printer is a type of printer with a print head that prints by impact, striking an ink-soaked cloth ribbon against the paper, much like a typewriter. Unlike a typewriter, letters are drawn out of a dot matrix, consisting of needles, and thus varied fonts and arbitrary graphics can be produced. Because the printing is done by applying mechanical pressure, these printers can create carbon copies.

Name: label printers
Description: Create your own, professional looking labels fast and conveniently with one of these label printers!

Name: large format printers
Description: These printers have been designed for printing on media larger than A4. Perfect for printing impressive posters!

Name: inkjet printers
Description: Inkjet printers are the most suitable printers for home and small office use. They are generally not as fast as laser printers, but make prints of very high quality and are quite affordable.

Name: laser/LED printers
Description: Laser printers are devices that print high quality text or illustrations fast. They do so by very accurately applying toner (a kind of ink powder) to the paper and then heating the paper so the toner will melt and stick to the paper.

Name: chassis components
Description: Components which fit inside the chassis, which is the metal shell used to protect computer parts. Examples of such components are motherboards and CPUs.

Name: computer cases
Description: A computer case, also known as a chassis, is an empty metal shell used to protect computer components.

Name: racks
Description: A type of metal shelf which contains servers.

Name: networks
Description: A telecommunications network which allows computers and other electronic devices to exchange data. Common examples are local area networks (LANs) and virtual private networks (VPNs).

Name: interface hubs
Description: An interface is a point of interaction with software, hardware or peripheral devices such as a computer monitor or keyboard. An interface hub is where there are several interfaces together in one place.

Name: routers
Description: With a router you can connect networks. Most people will use a router to connect their local (wireless) home or office network (LAN) with the Internet. The router makes sure that all computers on the local network can connect with one another, with shared resources and with the Internet and can be configured to forward requests for connections from computers on the internet to the appropriate local computer. In order to connect your local network to the internet via an ADSL or cable, you also need an (Ethernet) ADSL or cable modem if it is not built-in in the router, which is most likely to be the case.

Name: modems
Description: Device which converts digital data from computers into electric signals which can be transmitted over a telephone line, and convert electric signals which it receives into digital data for computers.

Name: network switches
Description: A switch is a device with which it is possible to connect computers into a (local area) network, provided your computers all have an appropriate networking device installed. Switches can be daisy chained to form larger networks and come in managed and unmanaged variaties. The unmanaged versions generally cannot filter data and will forward any data that is fed into them, so they are better suited for small networks. Switches are easy to set up (just plug in the network cables) and allow you to share printers, storage space and other network resources with your entire home or office network.

Name: KVM switches
Description: A keyboard, video, mouse (KVM) switch allows you to connect multiple computers to one keyboard, mouse, and display. You can switch between the different computers by a simple keystroke, without (un)plugging a single wire.

Name: data storage supplies
Description: Tape, disc or other device which can store data.

Name: diskettes
Description: Diskettes, also known as floppy disks or floppies for short, are a fairly old fashioned data storage medium. The big advantage of using floppy disks is that a lot of computers have a diskette drive, but a rather large disadvantage is that you can only store 1.4 MB on an ordinary 3.5" floppy.

Name: blank CDs
Description: Recordable CDs (CD-R) on which you can store your data in different formats, depending on the features of your CD/DVD Writer. If you want to record CDs at the maximum speed of your CD/DVD Writer, please make sure you pick CDs that support this speed. ReWritable CDs (CD-RW) are a special type of CD, which you can overwrite time and time again (up to some limited number). Ordinary CDs can only be used once.

Name: blank data tapes
Description: Empty data tapes for making back ups or storing huge amounts of data.

Name: high density removable media blank disks
Description: Blank disks that can store a large amount of data and can be removed from the device e.g CDs, DVDs.

Name: storage media cases
Description:
These goods will help you in organising your storage media collection, increasing its life time.

CD/DVD cases keep your CDs/DVDs clean and free of scratches and make them easy to organise.

Name: office
Description: An office is a room, floor or building where business is conducted.

Name: fax machines
Description: With a facsimile (fax) it is possible to send documents to and receive from other facsimiles; all you need is your existing phone line. Often facsimiles also have a copy (scan & print) function, although the quality of the copies is not always that great for most machines.

Name: multifunctionals
Description: A multifunctional is really an all-in-one device; it is both a scanner and a printer, and often even has a fax function. So effectively it's a copier, but one that has the scanning and printing functions available separately. All this is a great advantage when you have limited office space. Moreover, you will be able to work faster and more efficiently by using the device's convenient special functions.

Name: paper cutters
Description: Use a paper cutter to cut all your documents in the right format. A paper cutter is fast, efficient and the results are much better than those achieved with scissors.

Name: binding machines
Description: Organize all your documents by perforating them and storing them in ring binders. Give your reports a professional look, have them bound. With these devices you can do all that and more!

Name: duplex units
Description: Have your printer print on both sides of the paper automatically with one of these duplex units. Safv up to 50% on paper and work more efficiently when printing booklets. Save both money and the environment!

Name: trays & feeders
Description: Enlarge the input capacity of your printer with an extra tray, so you can print longer with less maintenance.

Name: calculators
Description: Small portable device used to perform arithmetic.

Name: lamination films
Description: Films such as plastic used to cover other materials such as paper.

Name: endorsers/imprinters
Description: Device which imprints something on another surface.

Name: typewriters
Description: Machine with a keyboard and a ribbon to print onto paper.

Name: laminators
Description: Using a laminator you can attach a clear, protective cover to your prints to make them more durable. Give the outside of reports a lasting professional look or make durable signs for use in public places!

Name: equipment cleansing kit
Description: Kit containing chemicals, cloths etc. used to clean equipment.

Name: fuser cleaning pads
Description: Cloths for cleaning the fuser in a laser printer or photocopier.

Name: fuser oil
Description: Fuser oil is used on the surface of the fuser roller in a photocopier to ensure that the toner does not stick to the paper and cause a paper jam.

Name: fusers
Description: Devices in laser printers or photocopiers which melts the toner onto the paper.

Name: printing supplies
Description: Supplies needed for printing such as ink cartridges and toners.

Name: printer belts
Description: Component in printers used to transfer colour onto paper.

Name: laser toner & cartridges
Description: Toner cartridges for your laser printer or copier.

Name: printer rollers
Description: Component in laser printers which is coated in toner particles which stick to the drum.

Name: ink sticks
Description: Some printers use ink sticks instead of cartridges. Be careful to pick the right product for your printer.

Name: developer units
Description: Component in laser printers linking the toner to the drum.

Name: printer drums
Description: Laser printers and copiers not only need toner (ink powder) for printing, but also a drum (comparable with the print head of an inkjet printer). The drum puts the toner in the right place, and afterwards the paper is heated so the toner melts and is attached permanently to the paper. Drums, like all components of a printer, wear and will have to be replaced at some time, although they are fairly durable.

Name: binding covers
Description: Hard covers used to protect books, printed reports etc.

Name: desk accessories & supplies
Description: Items needed for your desk such as lamps and  in-trays, as well as stationery such as notepaper and pens.

Name: desk trays
Description: Plastic object used to sort and store documents on your desk.

Name: cash & ticket boxes
Description: Boxes to hold cash and tickets. Usually made of metal and with a lock for security.

Name: drawing supplies
Description: Supplies used in drawing such as pencils, paints and paintbrushes.

Name: boards
Description: Place where information is put e.g. noticeboard, whiteboard in a classroom.

Name: planning boards
Description: Big board, usually a white board placed on a wall, where week/month/yearly plans can be written, erased and re-written.

Name: bulletin boards
Description: Board, often a pin board placed on a wall, to which bulletins, reports and other notes and posters are attached.

Name: magnetic boards
Description: Magnetic board where pieces of paper etc can be attached using magnets.

Name: planning systems
Description: System to plan a process, operation etc.

Name: address books
Description: Books for storing postal/e-mail addresses as well as other important information about your contacts.

Name: calendars
Description: Agendas showing the days, weeks and months of the year where you can add appointments and other important dates.

Name: mail supplies
Description: Supplies used for mailing such as envelopes and Jiffy bags.

Name: mailer tubes
Description: Cardboard or plastic tubes used for posting posters or other large rollable documents.

Name: envelopes
Description: Flat paper container with a sealable flap, used to enclose a letter or document.

Name: desk supplies
Description: Stationery such as notepaper and pens.

Name: staplers
Description: Device for fastening together sheets of paper together with a staple or staples.

Name: desk pads
Description: Pad placed on a desk to make it easier to write or to protect the desk from scratches.

Name: writing instruments
Description: Instruments used to write such as pens, pencils and market pens.

Name: rollerball pens
Description: Rollerball pens use a ball point and a water-based instead of an oil-based ink. The ink in a roller ball tends to go more deeply and more widely into the paper than the ink in a ball-point pen.

Name: fountain pens
Description: Pens with a metal nib and a removal ink cartridge.

Name: ball point pens
Description: Ball point pens use oil-based ink, which dries up almost immediately after applying on paper. The ink is evenly dispensed through a metal ball.

Name: colour pencils
Description: Pencils in diferent colours e.g red, blue, green.

Name: markers
Description: Ink pens used to make temporary or permanent markings (words, symbols, drawings) e.g non-permanent markers used on white boards.

Name: felt pens
Description: A felt pen is a type of marker pen with its own ink source. It's called a felt pen because of the porous felt tip from where the ink is applied on the surface.

Name: ink refills
Description: Replacement ink for ink cartridges etc.

Name: folders, binders & indexes
Description: Folders, binders and indexes are all made from strong paper, card or plastic and are used to store information or documents.

Name: index card trays
Description: Plastic trays used to store index cards.

Name: ring binders
Description: Folders with metal rings to keep papers and documents in order and prevent them from falling out.

Name: presentation materials
Description: Any materials used for presentation such as pens, flipcharts and paper.

Name: tab indexes
Description: Indexes with tabs to divide the sections. Often done alphabeticaly.

Name: dividers
Description: Sheet of card or paper used to divide a folder or ring binder into sections.

Name: folders
Description: Folding cover or holder, typically made of stiff paper or card, for storing loose papers.

Name: clipboards
Description: Small board with a spring clip at the top, used for holding papers and providing support for writing.

Name: report covers
Description: Covers, usually made of paper or card, used on the top of reports to protect them and sometimes to make them more visually appealing.

Name: paper clips
Description: Piece of bent wire or plastic used for holding several sheets of paper together.

Name: document clips
Description: Device used for holding documents together e.g. a bulldog clip which is typically made of metal and is silver and black.

Name: staples
Description: Piece of thin wire with two short right-angled end pieces which are driven by a stapler through sheets of paper to fasten them together.

Name: projectors
Description: Device that is used to project rays of light, especially an apparatus with a system of lenses for projecting slides or film on to a screen.

Name: pointers
Description: Used to indicate items on a screen. Can be a remote pointer or a graphical image on a screen such as a mouse cursor.

Name: projection lamps
Description: Lamp which enables a projector (beamer) to project/show images.

Name: projection screens
Description: Installation consisting of a surface and a support structure used for displaying a projected image for the view of an audience.

Name: data projectors
Description: Use a beamer to project the images from your notebook, computer, DVD-player, video recorder or other device with a compatible connector on the wall or a specially-designed projection screen. With a device like this, giving professional, clear presentations is easy. Or make your own home cinema!

Name: cameras
Description: A camera is a device used to capture images, as still photographs or as sequences of moving images (movies or videos). The term as well as the modern-day camera evolved from the camera obscura, Latin for "dark chamber", an early mechanism for projecting images, in which an entire room functioned as a real-time imaging system. Cameras may work with the light of the visible spectrum or with other portions of the electromagnetic spectrum. A camera generally consists of some kind of enclosed hollow, with an opening or aperture at one end for light to enter, and a recording or viewing surface for capturing the light at the other end. Most cameras have a lens positioned in front of the camera's opening to gather the incoming light and to focus the image, or part of the image, on the recording surface. The diameter of the aperture is often controlled by a diaphragm mechanism, but some cameras have a fixed-size aperture.

Name: digital cameras
Description: With a digital camera all the pictures you make are stored digitally, which means you can instantly view a picture after you have taken it and take as many pictures as you like, without having to buy new films all the time. It is easy to download the pictures from your camera to your computer, either at home or at the shop and edit them before printing. Once they are on your computer, you can easily share your pics with the rest of the world by putting them on-line, or e-mailing them to friends.

Name: webcams
Description: A webcam is a digital video camera that has to be connected directly to a computer or network and cannot be used seperately. Webcams are perfect for video calling and chatting: finally you can see your faraway friends or family while talking/chatting! Network attached webcams can be used as affordable security cameras.

Name: camcorders
Description: Hand-held camcorders allow you to record your own video and make photoshots. You can always have such cameras with you to record the important moments of your life and share them with friends or family. You can even make your own movie!

Name: camera accessories
Description: Accessories used with a camera such as cases and tripods.

Name: tripods
Description: Portable three-legged frame, used as a platform for supporting the weight and maintaining the stability of some other object such as a camera.

Name: camera lenses
Description: The light-gathering device of a camera, typically containing a group of compound lenses. Lenses come in different lengths, with very long lens used for long-distance photography.

Name: blank video tapes
Description: Video tapes which are blank so data can be recorded on them using a video recorder / VCR.

Name: printing media
Description: Different mediums which can support printed material, such as paper, card and plastic.

Name: plotter paper
Description: Paper used for printing vector graphics.

Name: writing notebooks
Description: Notebooks of various sizes, often containing lined/ruled paper, used for writinh notes.

Name: index cards
Description: Index cards are heavy pieces of paper cut to a standard size, used for recording and storing small amounts of discrete data.

Name: printing paper
Description: Paper for use with ink jet printers, often with a special coating that makes the ink dry faster and/or last longer without fading.

Name: business cards
Description: Small cards giving information and contact details about a employee or a company.

Name: software licenses/upgrades
Description: A software licence permits you to use a piece of software legally. An software upgrade is a newer or better version, in order to bring the software up to date or to improve its characteristics.

Name: security
Description: Security means protecting something, keeping it safe and meaning it cannot be attacked, infiltrated or otherwise damaged.

Name: computer cables
Description: Cables used to connect computers to power supplies and other devices such as printers.

Name: hardware firewalls
Description: By placing a firewall between your local network (LAN/WLAN) and the Internet, you can make it very hard for hackers to gain access to your local network. That is, if you have configured your firewall correctly. This can be especially important for businesses and people with sensitive information on their computer systems. A very neat function most hardware firewalls have is the ability to securely connect the local area network to other local area networks in different locations over the Internet, thus creating a Virtual Private Network (VPN). With VPN you can safely share network resources with remote offices or play games with your friends as if you were on the same LAN!

Name: gateways/controllers
Description: A gateway is a router or a proxy server that routes between networks. A controller is a chip, an expansion card, or a stand-alone device that interfaces with a peripheral device.

Name: ozone filters
Description: A filter for ozone is placed on a laser printer or copier to prevent ozone escaping into the air of the office.

Name: printer films
Description: Film that can be printed on and then used e.g. for presentations on projectors

Name: matt white films
Description: Film that can be printed on by laser printers and photocopies and then used for presentations and for signs.

Name: printable textiles
Description: Textiles which can be used in printers to print designs and text onto them.

Name: print heads
Description: These are part of inkjet printers, which prints ink onto paper. They are fixed heads, which are built into the printer, or disposable heads, which are built into the disposable ink carttridges.

Name: photo paper
Description: Photo paper has been specially designed for printing photographs. Use it to make perfect prints of your pictures!

Name: polypropylene films
Description: Also known as PP film, this is a type of plastic film.

Name: MP3/MP4 players
Description: MP3s are ways of compressing digitally-stored music and is the Internet-used standard. MP4s can be used to compress various types of data including music and video. MP3/MP4 players are small portable devices used to playing back music files. MP3/MP4 players are extremely small and most of them have no moving parts.

Name: transparancy films
Description: Transparent films can be printed on or written on directly. These can then be used in presentations with a projector.

Name: writing paper
Description: Paper used for writing, comes in various sizes and colours.

Name: remote controls
Description: These devices make it possible to control your home equipment from a distance. Never get up again!

Name: card readers
Description: Card readers and drives with built-in card readers are used for reading from/writing to flash memory cards, for example from your digital camera or cellphone.

Name: projector accessories
Description: Different accessories to be used with a proector such as a stand and screen.

Name: media spindles
Description: A plastic storage device for bundles of CDs, DVDS etc.

Name: hard drive enclosures
Description: A hard disk enclosure is a specialized casing designed to hold and power hard disks while providing a mechanism to allow them to communicate to one or more separate computers.

Name: wire connectors
Description: Wires to connect two or more components.

Name: bar code labels
Description: Labels for printing bar codes for products.

Name: power cables
Description: A power cable, also known as a power cord, is used for the transmission of electrical power.

Name: telephony cables
Description: Cables used to transmit telephone signals.

Name: networking cables
Description: Any type of network has its own type of cables. Today's standard for home and office use is Ethernet. For Fast Ethernet and Gigabit Ethernet you need at least category 5 cabling. Ethernet cables can have their connectors attached in two different ways: ordinary or cross linked. You will most likely need the ordinary version, unless you want to connect two devices directly to each other, and even then most modern Ethernet network devices will automatically detect the type of cable you are using and adapt their settings to it, so they will work with both types.

Name: email clients
Description: Computer program used to access and manage email.

Name: handheld device accessories
Description: Accessories for handheld devices such as screen protectors and cases.

Name: peripheral controllers
Description: These run a peripheral device and are either contained on a plug-in expansion board or on the motherboard. In larger computers, a controller may be contained on one or more boards or in an external, stand-alone cabinet.

Name: thin clients/blade PCs
Description: Client machine that relies on the server to perform the data processing. Either a dedicated thin client terminal or a regular PC with thin client software is used to send keyboard and mouse input to the server and receive screen output in return. The thin client does not process any data; it processes only the user interface (UI). The benefits are improved maintenance and security due to central administration of the hardware and software in the datacenter.

Name: tablets
Description: Mobile computer with display, circuitry and battery in a single unit. Tablets are equipped with sensors, including cameras, microphone, accelerometer and touchscreen, with finger or stylus gestures replacing computer mouse and keyboard.

Name: flash memory
Description: Flash memory comes in different types and is used by all kinds of products, e.g. cameras, MP3-players, telephones. The great advantage of flash memory is that it has no moving parts, so it is shock resistant and hardly wears. It is also very small and very light, which makes it perfect for use in portable digital devices.

Name: plasma TVs
Description: Plasma panels have fairly large pixels and are therefore mostly available in large sizes. These screens are flat and thin and their main advantage over LCD screens is that colours look the same, regardless of the angle from which you are viewing the screen. Plasma panels are very well suited for use as television or for displaying information and ads in public spaces.

Name: printer ribbons
Description: Ribbon for printers that need this for printing. Please make sure you purchase the right type for your printer.

Name: paper shredders
Description: Paper shredders cut up paper into small pieces so that the info on the paper cannot be read any more. This is important when disposing of paper which contains confidential information.

Name: WLAN access points
Description: With a WLAN (Wireless Local Area Network) access point you can build your own wireless network and share network resources like printers and storage space. You can even share one internet connection with your entire wireless local area network by connecting your access point (by Ethernet) to your (A)DSL or cable modem with built in router/DHCP server!

Name: navigators
Description: With a GPS (global positioning system) receiver you will always know where you are and never lose your way, because of a smart American satellite system which this device can receive signals from. With most GPS receivers it is possible to have your position displayed on a map and quite a few can even tell you the way to wherever you want to go, the only thing you need to do is tell it your destination!

Name: memory modules
Description: The Random Access Memory (RAM) is an important part of computers, servers and other electronic devices. Generally it is much faster than the permanent storage memory of your device and all information stored in it will be lost when you switch off your device. Extra RAM is often an affordable and efficient way to upgrade your slightly outdated device, so you can use it another year.

Name: printer cabinets & stands
Description: Cabinets and stands are places for your printer to elevate it from the floor.

Name: scanner transparancy adapters
Description: Many scanners come with a transparency adapter, which can be used to scan either slides or negatives. You tell the scanner driver which one, and it does the rest. Some are a secondary piece that you attach to the scanner bed when you need it, others have the transparency adapter internally.

Name: output stackers
Description: Have your prints stacked and/or stapled automatically with one of these convenient extras for your printer/copier.

Name: magneto optical drives
Description: Type of optical disc drive capable of writing and rewriting data upon a magneto-optical disc.

Name: computer cooling components
Description: Components which remove the waste heat produced by computer components, and keep components within permissible operating temperature limits.

Name: photo printers
Description: Photo printers allow you to print digital photos, often they can even print directly from a digital camera, so you do not even need a computer to print your photos. Having such a printer at home, you can forget the photolabs!

Name: audio modules
Description: Module that can produce audio output. They plug into a main system in a computer.

Name: print servers
Description: Connect one or more printers directly to your Local Area Network and share it/them with all the computers on your network, using one of these print servers.

Name: NAS & storage servers
Description: Multifunctional data storage servers that allow you to store huge amounts of data. Connect your storage server directly to your own PC or share it with your local area network, so anybody in your home/office can use it. You can even connect it to the internet and share your data securely with friends or colleagues at a remote office via a VPN connection or if you would wish to do so you could even share your data with the whole world via ftp (provided your server supports this).

Name: microphones
Description: Instrument for converting sound waves into electrical energy variations which may then be amplified, transmitted, or recorded.

Name: flat panels accessories
Description: Accessories for flat panel TVs and monitors such as stands and desk mounts.

Name: flat panel desk mounts
Description:
A comfortable, ergonomic computer workstation requires an adjustable computer monitor arm or monitor stand. We offer monitor arms and stands for any budget that help make your computer work easier, pain free and more productive.



Main ergonomic recommendations for monitor use include moving your monitor to a comfortable distance of around an arm's length and position the monitor at a comfortable height of about 2"-3" above eye level. Choose one of our many stylish monitor arms and stands and free up valuable desktop space.

Name: display privacy filters
Description: Glare is a common cause of eyestrain among computer users. Glare screens or monitor filters can be used to reduce the glare or the wash out but they do not eliminate the glare problems entirely. Therefore, placing the monitor perpendicular to your windows or obtaining window blinds to prevent the glare on the screen should be the first consideration.

Name: coaxial cables
Description: Coaxial cable, also known as a coax, is a type of cable that has an inner conductor surrounded by a tubular insulating layer, surrounded by a tubular conducting shield. Many coaxial cables also have an insulating outer sheath or jacket. Various uses including home video equipment and ethernets.

Name: large format media
Description: Large format media include billboard posters and large outdoor screens.

Name: cable locks
Description: Cable with a locking mechanism already permanently integrated.

Name: printer kits
Description: Components needed to build a printer.

Name: stapler units
Description: Component in a printer or photocopier that can staple documents together.

Name: imaging units
Description: Component of a printer or photocopier which is sometimes referred to as copier cartridge, toner cartridge, or drum unit. An imaging unit in which all or many of the consumable and maintenance items, such as toner, developer, photoconductor, corona wires, wiper blade, etc. are sometimes combined in one module which may be user-disposable/recyclable.

Name: processors
Description: The Central Processing Unit (CPU) or (micro) processor is the part of a computer where most calculations take place. In terms of computing power, the processor is the most important element of a computer system, so the performance of a computer is highly dependant on the performance of the processor. For quite some time the performance of a processor has been determined by the number of MHz the clock speed was, but nowadays clock speed doesn't have so much to do with the speed of the processor anymore. One of the best ways to compare different kinds of processors, is to look up benchmarks on the internet. Please be careful to buy a processor that is compatible with your motherboard, i.e. fits in the right socket.

Name: holders
Description: Object which can be used to contain other objects e.g. a drinks holder in a cinema seat.

Name: DVD players
Description: With the help of DVD players/recorders you can watch/record videos of high quality, play MP3-CDs, audio CDs and audio DVDs, as well as look through your photos in JPG format. DVD recorders often have an in-built hard disk on which you can record your home videos, edit them and burn them to DVD afterwards, or record your favourite TV programmes so you can watch them later. Some DVD recorders even have automatic ad recognition: simply start watching the movie half an hour or so after the broadcast started and it will skip all those unwanted advertisements for you, so you never need to watch any ads if you don't want to!

Name: mounting kits
Description: A kit that is designed to help in the installation of an external antenna or wireless networking device system.

Name: network media converters
Description: Device which changes signals on a copper cable to signals that run on fiber, letting a company introduce fiber in the network without making other changes.

Name: printer labels
Description: Print your own professional looking labels!

Name: tapes
Description: Narrow strip of material, typically used to hold or fasten something.

Name: glues
Description: Adhesive substance used for sticking objects or materials together.

Name: postal scales
Description: Scales used to weigh objects that need to be posted in order to determine the cost of postage.

Name: headphones
Description: Headphones come in all sorts of designs and qualities, so you will surely be able to find your perfect pair in our database!

Name: laminator pouches
Description: This is a transparent plastic pouch which can be used to cover a sheet of paper. This is then passed through a pouch laminatior machine and the open end of the pouch is sealed, so the paper is laminated.

Name: typewriter ribbons
Description: Device which transfers pigment to paper in various devices for impact printing. Such ribbons were part of standard designs for hand- or motor-driven typewriters, teleprinters, stenotype machines, computer-driven printers and many mechanical calculators, before electronic alternatives replaced most of them.

Name: toner collectors
Description: Container which collects excess toner that is produced during printing.

Name: pen & pencil holders
Description: Objects, commonly made of plastic, which can hold and store pens and pencils. Usually found on desk tops.

Name: file storage boxes & organizers
Description: Boxes and other places to store files .

Name: document holders
Description: Card or plastic files/folders used to contain documents.

Name: hanging folders & accessories
Description: Folders which are used in filing cabinets to store documents.

Name: folder binding accessories
Description: Accessories for storing documents in folder binders, such as card dividers.

Name: thermal binding machines
Description: Machines that use heat to bind documents together.

Name: wrist rests
Description: To prevent Repetited Strain Injury (RSI), a painful, numb feeling in your arm(s), wrist(s) and/or hands(s) during and after working with a computer for a prolonged period of time, it is important to have an ergonomical posture while working. A wrist rest for use with your mouse prevents flexion of the wrist, thus reducing the risk of getting a so called 'mouse wrist', RSI in the wrist. A wrist rest for use with a keyboard is not intended for resting your wrist on while working. Use it only for during breaks, to prevent your wrists from unncessary strain.

Name: fineliners
Description: Pen with a thin nib, used for drawing and writing.

Name: photo albums
Description: Books with a hard cover used to display photos.

Name: self-adhesive labels
Description: Labels that can be stuck onto envelopes, files etc. Used for naming and labelling things. Have a sticky back so will stick without the need for glue.

Name: addressing labels
Description: Labels that are used for envelopes and parcels to write the addressee's details, and sometimes that of the sender.

Name: flat panel wall mounts
Description: Supports, usually made out of metal, that are attached to the wall and used to hang a flat panel screen for a TV or a computer.

Name: audio & video
Description: Audio means sound , especially when recorded, transmitted, or reproduced, such as with a CD player. Vidoe is the recording, reproducing, or broadcasting of moving visual images.

Name: correction ribbons
Description: An inked strip of cloth used in typewriters to correct mistakes in typing.

Name: fax ribbons
Description: An inked strip of cloth used for printing faxes onto fax paper in a fax machine.

Name: office furniture
Description: Chairs, desks, filing cabinets, bookshelves and other furniture for the office.

Name: blank DVDs
Description: Burn your own movies or important data to a DVD disk for storage or for sharing with family, friends and colleagues. Please be careful to purchase the right type of DVD: there is a difference between DVD+R and DVD-R recordable DVDs and not all recorders support both formats. DVD+RW disks are rewritable DVDs and DVD DL is short for DVD Dual Layer, which means you can store 8.5 GB of data on this type of DVD instead of the usual 4.7 GB.

Name: whiteboards
Description: A glossy, usually white surface for non-permanent markings. Whiteboards are analogous to chalkboards/blackboard, allowing rapid marking and erasing of markings on their surface.

Name: non-adhesive labels
Description: Labels that do not stick to the surface to which they are applied.

Name: paper perforators
Description: Manual or electric device used for making perforations (holes) in paper.

Name: zip disks
Description: 3.5" removable disk drive from Iomega. Zip disks came in 100MB, 250MB and 750MB varieties, with the latter introduced in 2002 using USB and FireWire interfaces.The drive was bundled with software that could catalog the disks and lock the files for security.

Name: LCD TVs
Description: LCD is a technology for displaying images. LCD screens are flat, thin and have a reasonably high resolution and are therefore much used as computer monitor, but are also very suitable for use in a television!

Name: loudspeakers
Description: Apparatus that converts electrical impulses into sound, typically as part of a public address system.

Name: home cinema systems
Description: Take the movies home with one of these fantastic home cinema systems! A home cinema system generally contains everything you need to enjoy the most realistic display of your DVDs or videogames: a DVD player, an amplifier and surround speakers with subwoofer, and it all works perfectly together. The only thing that's not included is a TV, leaving you the freedom to choose one yourself, you could even add a beamer instead of a TV, for the real home cinema experience!

Name: dictaphones
Description: Small devices which records audio (normally speech) and can play it back at a later time.

Name: cleaning wipes for office
Description: Cloths for cleaning offices, office furniture and office equipment.

Name: flipovers
Description: Also known as a flipchart, this is a large pad of paper bound so that each page can be turned over at the top to reveal the next, used on a stand at presentations.

Name: coat racks
Description: An item of furniture on which coats can be hung. It often consists of a set of hooks that are attached to a wall.

Name: personal organizers
Description: Small book or binder that is designed to be portable. It usually contains a diary, calendar, address book, blank paper, and other sections.

Name: T-shirt transfers
Description: Designs which can be ironed onto T-shirts.

Name: permanent markers
Description: Pens used to make a permanent mark on surfaces, such as CDs and DVDs.

Name: projector cases
Description: Hard or padded cases used for protecting and transporting projectors.

Name: art paper
Description: Good-quality paper, usually white, which is used for drawing or painting. Comes in various sizes including A4 and A3 .

Name: printer cables
Description: Cables to connect printers to computers and other devices.

Name: USB cables
Description: Cable used to connect to a USB port, which are found in desktop computers, laptops and other electronic devices.

Name: seals
Description: Device or substance that is used to join two things together so as to prevent them coming apart or to prevent anything passing between them.

Name: binding kits
Description: Kits used for binding documents together.

Name: easels
Description: Wooden frame for holding an artists work while it is being painted or drawn.

Name: dry erase boards
Description: Also known as a whiteboard, this is a glossy, usually white surface for nonpermanent markings.

Name: key chains & cases
Description: Key chains are pieces of metal which are used for carrying keys. Key cases are objects used for carrying keys.

Name: freestanding tables
Description: Tables which can stand alone. They are not attached to anything.

Name: label-making tapes
Description: Tapes which can be used to make labels.

Name: carbon paper
Description: Paper coated on one side with a layer of a loosely bound dry ink or pigmented coating. Used for making one or more copies simultaneous with the creation of an original document when using a typewriter or a ballpoint pen.

Name: MP3/MP4 player accessories
Description: Accessories used with MP3/MP4 players such as earphones.

Name: notebook accessories
Description: Accessories used with notebooks (small computers) such as cases.

Name: notebook cases
Description: Take your notebook with you in a safe, comfortable and ergonomic way; use one of these specially designed bags or cases!

Name: camera kits
Description: A camera kit contains all of the apparatus you need to build a camera.

Name: camera cases
Description: Take your camera anywhere safely, with one of these comfortable camera cases.

Name: peripheral devices cases
Description: Cases used to contain mobile devcies such as cameras and notebooks.

Name: AV receivers
Description: Audio/video (AV) receivers receive audio and video signals.

Name: SATA cables
Description: SATA is a computer bus interface that connects host bus adapters to mass storage devices such as hard disk drives and optical drives. SATA host adapters and devices communicate via a high-speed serial cable over two pairs of conductors.

Name: print & scan accessories
Description: Accessories needed for printing and scanning such as ink cartridges and printer paper.

Name: AV cables
Description: AV (Audio Video) cables are used in audio and video equipment such as DVD players and loudspeakers.

Name: home audio sets
Description: Includes speakers, amplifiers and various types of music-playing device such as CD player or cassette deck. Can also include a radio receiver/tuner.

Name: flat panel floor stands
Description: Stands used to erect a flat panel screen on the floor.

Name: digital media players
Description: Media players unite your network with your home entertainment center, allowing you to share, access, and enjoy your digital media, whether it's music, videos, or photos, in the comfort of your living room. Some media players even have a built-in hard disk, so you can store your favourite movies or music and enjoy them without having your computer on.

Name: mechanical pencils
Description: Also known as a retractable pencil, this is a pencil with a replaceable and mechanically extendable lead.

Name: audio/video cassettes
Description: Sealed plastic object containing a length of audio or videotape, wound on a pair of spools, for insertion into a recorder, playback device, or other machine.

Name: mobile device chargers
Description: Used to plug mobile devices into mains electricity or other power sources to recharge batteries.

Name: magneto optical disks
Description: Type of disk used to store digital data, such as a MiniDisc.

Name: badges/badge holders
Description: A badge is a small piece of metal, plastic, or cloth bearing a design or words, typically worn to identify a person or to indicate membership of an organization or support for a cause. A badge holder is a small transparent plastic object used to hold a badge and attach it onto someone or something.

Name: business card holders
Description: Containers, usually made of plastic, for keeping business cards.

Name: board cleaning kits
Description: Clothes and cleaning fluids used for cleaning boards.

Name: headphone pillows
Description: A pillow which has in-built speakers so can play music when plugged into a MP3 player or other digital music device.

Name: thermal paper
Description: A special fine paper that is coated with a chemical that changes color when exposed to heat. It is used in thermal printers and particularly in inexpensive or lightweight devices such as adding machines, cash registers, and credit card terminals.

Name: cable ties
Description: A cable tie is a type of fastener, especially for binding several electronic cables together and to organize them into a cable tree.

Name: KVM cables
Description: A KVM (Keyboard Video Mouse) cable connects a keyboard, mouse and monitor to two or more computers.

Name: paperclip dispensers
Description: Containers for paperclips, which are used to dispense paperclips one at a time.

Name: mobile phone cables
Description: Cable which connects a mobile phone to a charger, computer or other electronic device.

Name: rack consoles
Description: Frame or cabinet into which hardware components are mounted.

Name: cable interface/gender adapters
Description: Small device which is connected to a cable to change from male to female connections or vice-versa.

Name: docking speakers
Description: A speaker to which a mobile music device such as MP3 player can be directly connected and then used to play the music on the device.

Name: notebook arms & stands
Description: Devices used to rest and support notebook computers to make then easier to use.

Name: AV equipment stands
Description: Stands for audio-visual equipment such as speakers and CD players.

Name: video splitters
Description: Devices that allow a single video input to be connected to multiple outputs.

Name: patch panels
Description: Number of circuits, usually of the same or similar type, which appear on jacks for monitoring, interconnecting, and testing circuits in a convenient, flexible manner.

Name: rack accessories
Description: Shelves, arms and other components of racks.

Name: input device accessories
Description: An input device is any peripheral (piece of computer hardware equipment) used to provide data and control signals to an information processing system such as a computer or other information appliance. Examples of input devices include keyboards, mouse, scanners, digital cameras and joysticks. Input device accessories include the components for input devices.

Name: USB flash drives
Description: Also known as a USB stick or a USB pen, these are small devices with a USB connector which can be connected to a computer or other electronic device and used to store data.

Name: solid state drives
Description: Aso known as a solid state disk or electronic disk, this is a data storage device for a computer using integrated circuit assemblies as memory to store data persistently.

Name: screen protectors
Description: Plastic covers used to protect smartphone and tablet screens from scratching etc.

Name: e-book readers
Description: Electronic device used to display e-books.

Name: LED TVs
Description:
A LED-TV is a flat panel display that uses LED backlighting instead of the cold cathode fluorescent (CCFL) backlighting used in most other LCDs. Three forms of LED may be used:

- White edge-LEDs around the rim of the screen, using a special diffusion panel to spread the light evenly behind the screen (the most usual form)

- An array of LEDs arranged behind the screen whose brightness are not controlled individually.

- A dynamic local dimming array of LEDs to achieve a modulated backlight light pattern

Name: Blu-Ray players
Description: Devices which play Blu-Ray Discs. Used in home entertainment and home cinema systems to play films.

Name: blank BDs
Description: These are blank Blu-Ray Discs (BDs) onto which you can store data e.g. films.

Name: telecommunication terminal units
Description: Instrument that converts user information into signals or reconverts received signals.

Name: document management software
Description: Computer programs used to track and store electronic documents. It is usually also capable of keeping track of the different versions modified by different users (history tracking). The term has some overlap with the concepts of content management systems. It is often viewed as a component of enterprise content management (ECM) systems and related to digital asset management, document imaging, workflow systems and records management systems.

Name: headsets
Description: Headsets are headphone or headphones combined with a microphone. Headsets provide the equivalent functionality of a telephone handset but with hands-free operation. They have many uses including in call centers and other telephone-intensive jobs and for anybody wishing to have both hands free during a telephone conversation.

Name: stereoscopic 3D glasses
Description: Pairs of glasses which allow 2D images to be perceived as 3D. They present two offset images separately to the left and right eye of the viewer. These two-dimensional images are then combined in the brain to give the perception of 3D depth.

Name: IP phones
Description: An Internet Protocol (IP) phone, also known as a VoIP phone (Voice over IP) uses technologies for placing and transmitting telephone calls over an IP network, such as the Internet, instead of the traditional public switched telephone network (PSTN).

Name: cellular wireless network equipment
Description: Equipment used to create a cellular wireless (mobile phone and internet) network such as antennas.

Name: camera filters
Description: Filters used on cameras to modify the images recorded e.g. to change the colours or to make black-white images. The filter can be a square or oblong shape mounted in a holder accessory, or, more commonly, a glass or plastic disk with a metal or plastic ring frame, which can be screwed in front of or clipped onto the lens.

Name: digital video recorders
Description: Sometimes referred to by the merchandising term personal video recorder (PVR),this is a consumer electronics device or application software that records video in a digital format to a disk drive, USB flash drive, SD memory card, SSD or other local or networked mass storage device. The term includes set-top boxes (STB) with direct to disk recording facility, portable media players (PMP) with recording, recorders (PMR) as camcorders that record onto Secure Digital memory cards and software for personal computers which enables video capture and playback to and from a hard disk drive.

Name: notebook cooling pads
Description: Accessory for notebook computers that helps reduce their operating temperature.They are intended to protect both the notebook from overheating and the user from suffering heat-related discomfort.

Name: two-way radios
Description: Radio that can both transmit and receive. A two-way radio allows the operator to have a conversation with other similar radios operating on the same radio frequency (channel). Two-way radios are available in mobile, stationary base and hand-held portable configurations. Hand-held radios are often called walkie-talkies.

Name: service management software
Description: Computer program that allows you to manage a service such as online retail.

Name: video switches
Description: Device with multiple ports which allows separate computers to display their video outputs on a single screen.

Name: remote power controllers
Description: Device that allows power to be controlled remotely.

Name: RAID controllers
Description: RAID is a storage technology that combines multiple disk drive components into a logical unit for the purposes of data redundancy and performance improvement. Data is distributed across the drives in one of several ways, referred to as RAID levels, depending on the specific level of redundancy and performance required. A RIAD controller, which is a type of disk array controller, is a device which manages the physical disk drives and presents them to the computer as logical units.

Name: projector mounts
Description: Object which is placed on the floor or attached to the ceiling or wall, used to hold a projector in place.

Name: CPU mounts
Description: Object which supports a CPU (Central Processing Unit in a computer) and holds it in place.

Name: flat panel ceiling mounts
Description: Bracket or support used to hang a flat panel from the ceiling.

Name: wall & ceiling mounts accessories
Description: Accessories for wall and ceiling mounts such as screws, nuts and brackets.

Name: network switch modules
Description: A network switch is a computer networking device that is used to connect many devices together on a computer network. A network switch module is a self-contained hardware or software component that interfaces between a network switch and other devices.

Name: printer memory
Description: Memory (RAM) built into the printer, which is used to store and process print jobs sent from the computer.

Name: external hard drives
Description: Stand-alone magnetic disk, optical disc or solid state drive that plugs into the computer typically via USB, although eSATA and FireWire are also used. Used for storing and retrieving digital information.

Name: interactive whiteboards
Description: Large interactive display that connects to a computer. A projector projects the computer's desktop onto the board's surface where users control the computer using a pen, finger, stylus, or other device. The board is typically mounted to a wall or floor stand. Used in schools and corporate meeting rooms.

Name: speaker sets
Description: Collection of speakers in a home audio system.

Name: network transceiver modules
Description: Device comprising both a transmitter and a receiver which are used in computer networks.

Name: soundbar speakers
Description: Sspecial loudspeaker enclosure that creates a reasonable stereo effect from a single cabinet. They are much wider than they are tall, partly for acoustical reasons, but also so that they can be mounted above or below a display device e.g. above a computer monitor or under a television or home theater screen.

Name: smartphones
Description: Mobile phone that is able to perform many of the functions of a computer, typically having a relatively large screen and an operating system capable of running general-purpose applications.

Name: AV extenders
Description: Devices which distribute audio and video signals over long distances.

Name: cash handling supplies
Description: Equipment used for cash handling such as coin bags and security boxes.

Name: network extenders
Description: Device that extends the range of a network or interconnects two different types of networks.

Name: document cameras
Description: Real-time image capture devices for displaying an object to a large audience. Like an opaque projector, a document camera is able to magnify and project the images of actual, three-dimensional objects, as well as transparencies. They are, in essence, high resolution web cams, mounted on arms so as to facilitate their placement over a page. This allows a teacher, lecturer or presenter to write on a sheet of paper or to display a two or three-dimensional object while the audience watches.

Name: headphone/headset accessories
Description: Accessories for headphones/headsets such as speakers, conenctors and cables.

Name: HDD/SSD docking stations
Description: Device in which a Hard Disk Drive (HDD) or Solid-State Drive (SSD) is placed. Data from the HDD/SDD can then transferred onto the electronic device connected to the docking station e.g. smartphone, or vice-versa.

Name: audio switches
Description: Device which can switch between various audio inputs either manually or sequentially.

Name: action sports cameras
Description: Cameras in a hard protective cover used for action sports such as skiing or skateboarding.

Name: portable speakers
Description: Small devices designed to be carried and plugged into smartphones, MP3 players etc to make a portable audio entertainment system.

Name: video surveillance kits
Description: Video cameras, wires, recording devices etc. used to set up a video surveillance system (CCTV).

Name: lighting
Description: Equipment in a room, building, or street for producing light.

Name: instant picture films
Description: Films where pictures are developed/printed instantly e.g. Polaroid cameras

Name: lamps
Description: Device for giving light, usually consisting of an electric bulb together with its holder and shade or cover.

Name: flashlights
Description: Also known as a torch, this is a portable electric light usually powered by AA or AAA batteries.

Name: LED lamps
Description: Light-emitting diode (LED) product that is assembled into a lamp (or light bulb) for use in lighting fixtures. LED lamps have a lifespan and electrical efficiency that is several times better than incandescent lamps, and significantly better than most fluorescent lamps, with some chips able to emit more than 100 lumens per watt.

Name: desk drawer organizers
Description: Plastic trays which are placed in desk drawers to allow you to organize things into different compartments.

Name: staple removers
Description: Item used to manually take staples out of documents

Name: scissors
Description: Instrument used for cutting cloth, paper, and other material, consisting of two blades laid one on top of the other and fastened in the middle so as to allow them to be opened and closed by a thumb and finger inserted through rings on the end of their handles.

Name: notebook filler paper
Description: Lined/ruled paper used in notebooks or placed into folders/binders. Often with punch holes in the left hand margin to allow easy storage.

Name: cushioning
Description: To protect from impacts or other disturbing effects e.g. shock absorbers on a car.

Name: key cabinets & organizers
Description: Key cabinets are small cupboards with multiple hooks for storing keys.

Name: foot rests
Description: Small piece of furniture, usually made of plastic, which you place under a desk or table and rest your feet on to make it more comfortable to sit.

Name: filing cabinets
Description: Piece of office furniture used to store paper documents in file folders. Normally made of metal and with 3 or 4 drawers.

Name: paint markers
Description: A paint marker is a type of marker pen that is used to create permanent writing on a variety of surfaces from paper to metal to stone. Unlike most permanent markers the ink is an oil based paint and generally requires shaking before use. (Paint markers like permanent markers generally contain the toxic compounds xylene or toluene and require some safety when used.)

Name: showcases
Description: Cases used for displaying items or artefacts.

Name: sign holders
Description: Metal stands used to hold signs, such as those seen outside shops or inside conference centres.

Name: bookmarks
Description: Strip of leather, card, or other material, used to mark ones place in a book.

Name: computer furniture parts
Description: Parts for computer furniture such as computer desks.

Name: mats
Description: Large mats are piece of coarse material placed on a floor for people to wipe their feet on. Small mats are made from cork, card, or fabric and are placed on a table or other surface to protect it from the heat or moisture of an object placed on it. A computer mouse often needs a mouse mat to work effectively.

Name: multimedia carts & stands
Description: Small table or cabinet on wheels or castors, used to store and transport multimedia equipment such as projectors.

Name: pen refills
Description: Small tube of ink for a pen where the ink can be replaced.

Name: paper cutters accessories
Description: A paper cutter, also known as a paper trimmer, paper guillotine, or guillotine is a tool often found in offices and classrooms, designed to cut a large set of paper at once with a perfectly straight edge. Accessories for paper cutters include spare blades and rulers.

Name: paper shredders accessories
Description: A paper shredder is mechanical device used to cut paper into strips or fine particles. Government organizations, businesses, and private individuals use shredders to destroy private, confidential, or otherwise sensitive documents. Paper shredder accessories include bags for the shredded paper.

Name: gel pens
Description: Pen which uses ink in which pigment is suspended in a water-based gel. Because the ink is thick and opaque, it shows up more clearly on dark or slick surfaces than the typical inks used in ballpoint or felt tip pens. Gel pens can be used for many types of writing and illustration.

Name: cutter knives
Description: Small sharp knives used for cutting card and plastic. Often with a retractable or protected blade e.g. Stanley knife.

Name: note paper dispensers
Description: Small plastic container placed on desks which dispenses notepaper.
